<i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Matida Ellen Spurstowe was born in 1412, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Spurstowe, was 20 and her mother, Spurstowe, was 20. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Thomas Cottingham. She died in 1446, in her hometown, at the age of 34."},"et":{"1412–1446":"1412–1446","1418–1481":"1418–1481","1434–1517":"1434–1517","1437–1517":"1437–1517","1437–Male":"1437–Surnud","1392–Male":"1392–Surnud","1392–Female":"1392–Surnud","1437":"1437","1446":"1446","1412":"1412","1434":"1434","1481":"1481","1392":"1392","1517":"1517","1418":"1418","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lea by Nantwich, Cheshire, England":"Lea by Nantwich, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Cottingham, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1412–1446":"1412